  <p class="intro">
    Web development is the art of building websites and web applications. From simple landing pages
    to complex platforms like social networks, web developers create the digital experiences we use every day.
  </p>

  <h2 id="introduction">What is Web Development?</h2>
  <p>
    Web development encompasses everything involved in building websites: writing code, designing layouts,
    setting up servers, and managing databases. It's typically divided into two main areas:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Frontend (Client-side):</strong> What users see and interact with in their browser</li>
    <li><strong>Backend (Server-side):</strong> The logic, databases, and servers that power the application</li>
    <li><strong>Full-stack:</strong> Developers who work on both frontend and backend</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Why Learn Web Development?</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High demand:</strong> Every business needs a web presence</li>
    <li><strong>Creative + technical:</strong> Blend design with problem-solving</li>
    <li><strong>Immediate results:</strong> See your work come to life in the browser</li>
    <li><strong>Low barrier to entry:</strong> Start with just a text editor and browser</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="how-web-works">How the Web Works</h2>
  <p>
    Understanding the fundamentals helps you become a better developer. Here's what happens when you visit a website:
  </p>

  <h3>The Request-Response Cycle</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>You type a URL</strong> in your browser (e.g., www.example.com)</li>
    <li><strong>DNS lookup</strong> translates the domain name to an IP address</li>
    <li><strong>Browser sends a request</strong> to the server at that IP address</li>
    <li><strong>Server processes the request</strong> and prepares a response</li>
    <li><strong>Server sends back HTML, CSS, and JavaScript</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Browser renders the page</strong> for you to see</li>
  </ol>

