  <h3>Backend Responsibilities</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>API endpoints:</strong> Handle requests from the frontend</li>
    <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> User login, sessions, JWT tokens</li>
    <li><strong>Database operations:</strong> CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete)</li>
    <li><strong>Business logic:</strong> Rules, calculations, validations</li>
    <li><strong>Security:</strong> Input validation, encryption, protection against attacks</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="databases">Databases</h2>
  <p>
    Databases store and organize your application's data. There are two main types:
  </p>

  <h3>SQL (Relational) Databases</h3>
  <p>Store data in tables with defined relationships. Great for structured data.</p>
  <pre><code>{`-- Example SQL query
SELECT users.name, orders.total
FROM users
JOIN orders ON users.id = orders.user_id
WHERE orders.total > 100;`}</code></pre>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>PostgreSQL:</strong> Feature-rich, great for complex queries</li>
    <li><strong>MySQL:</strong> Popular, widely supported</li>
    <li><strong>SQLite:</strong> Lightweight, file-based (great for learning)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>NoSQL Databases</h3>
  <p>Flexible schema, great for unstructured or rapidly changing data.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>MongoDB:</strong> Document-based, JSON-like storage</li>
    <li><strong>Redis:</strong> In-memory, great for caching</li>
    <li><strong>Firebase:</strong> Real-time database, great for mobile apps</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="apis">APIs & REST</h2>
  <p>
    APIs (Application Programming Interfaces) allow different software systems to communicate.
    REST is the most common architectural style for web APIs.
  </p>

  <h3>RESTful API Principles</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Resources:</strong> Everything is a resource (users, posts, products)</li>
    <li><strong>HTTP Methods:</strong> GET (read), POST (create), PUT (update), DELETE (remove)</li>
    <li><strong>Stateless:</strong> Each request contains all needed information</li>
    <li><strong>JSON:</strong> Standard format for data exchange</li>
  </ul>

  <pre><code>{`// Example API request with JavaScript
fetch('https://api.example.com/users')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(users => console.log(users))
  .catch(error => console.error('Error:', error));`}</code></pre>

